<div class="content">
    <p>
    During my Masters in Systems Design Engineering at the University of Waterloo, I worked on modeling and simulation of the golf swing.  The goal of my research was to investigate a variety of parameters involved in the design of golf clubs and determine their effects on the ability of the golfer to drive the ball as far as possible.  
    </p>
    <p>
    The model consists of four stages.  The first stage is a biomechanical model of the golfer that incorporates the motion of the torso, arm, wrist, and hands of the golfer.  These are activated by torque generators that take into account muscle dynamics.  The second stage of the model is a flexible club, modeled using Rayleigh beam theory that is able to calculate the position of the clubhead throughout the swing incorporating the flexing and twisting motions.  
    </p>    

