    <p>
    Once the club is swung by the simulated golfer, the third stage of the model calculates the initial ball velocity and sping using a 3-D impulse-momentum approach.  Finally, an aerodynamic simulation is performed to calculate the carry or the distance that the ball was hit.  
    </p>
    <p>
    To accommodate swinging different clubs, the entire model is subject to an optimization procedure that selects the best joint torque profiles for the muscles in the golfer portion of the model for a particular club.  Different club parameters can then be varied within the simulation and their effect measured.  
    </p>

    <p>
    I presented an earlier stage of this research at the <a href="http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877705814006547">International Sports Engineering Association conference</a> in Sheffield England in Summer 2014.  The final version is available <a href="https://uwspace.uwaterloo.ca/handle/10012/9158">as my thesis</a> and will submitted to other journals.
    </p>
    
